                    </div>
                    <div class="progress-bar">
                        <div class="progress-fill" id="progressFill" style="width: 0%"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="summary-grid">
                    <div class="summary-card">
                        <div class="summary-label">Target</div>
                        <div class="summary-value" id="summaryTarget">0g</div>
                        <div class="summary-detail">daily protein</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="summary-card">
                        <div class="summary-label">Planned</div>
                        <div class="summary-value" id="summaryPlanned">0g</div>
                        <div class="summary-detail">total in plan</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="summary-card">
                        <div class="summary-label">Per Meal Avg</div>
                        <div class="summary-value" id="summaryPerMeal">0g</div>
                        <div class="summary-detail">protein average</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <button type="button" class="regenerate-btn" onclick="regeneratePlan()">Regenerate Entire Plan</button>

                <div id="mealPlanContainer"></div>

                <div class="card" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
                    <div class="section-title">Protein Sources Breakdown</div>
                    <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                        <table class="breakdown-table" id="breakdownTable">
                            <thead>
                                <tr>
                                    <th>Food</th>
                                    <th>Servings</th>
                                    <th>Protein</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody id="breakdownBody"></tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="card" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
                    <div class="section-title">Top 20 Protein Sources per Calorie</div>
                    <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                        <table class="ref-table" id="refTable">
                            <thead>
                                <tr>
                                    <th>#</th>
                                    <th>Food</th>
                                    <th>Protein</th>
                                    <th>Calories</th>
                                    <th>g/100cal</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody id="refBody"></tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="card faq-section">
                    <div class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much protein do I need per day for muscle building?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">For muscle building, research recommends 1.6&ndash;2.2 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight per day. For an 80 kg (176 lb) person, that&rsquo;s 128&ndash;176g of protein daily. Spreading this across 3&ndash;5 meals with 25&ndash;40g per meal optimizes muscle protein synthesis.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I get enough protein on a vegan diet?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, you can meet high protein targets on a vegan diet by combining foods like tofu, tempeh, seitan, lentils, chickpeas, edamame, hemp seeds, and pea protein. The key is variety &mdash; combining different plant proteins throughout the day ensures you get all essential amino acids.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What are the best high-protein foods per calorie?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">The most protein-dense foods per calorie include chicken breast (31g protein per 165 cal), egg whites (11g per 52 cal), shrimp (24g per 99 cal), turkey breast (29g per 135 cal), and cottage cheese (14g per 98 cal). Check the reference table above for the full top 20 ranking.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How should I distribute protein across meals?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Research shows that distributing protein evenly across meals (20&ndash;40g per meal) maximizes muscle protein synthesis better than eating most protein in one meal. Aim for at least 20g of protein at breakfast, which most people under-eat.</div></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is it better to eat 3 or 5 meals for protein intake?</button>
                        <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">For protein intake above 120g per day, eating 4&ndash;5 meals makes it easier to hit your target without feeling overly full at each meal. Each meal can deliver 25&ndash;35g of protein, which is the optimal range for muscle protein synthesis per sitting.</div></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How to Plan High-Protein Meals</h2>
            <p>Planning protein-rich meals starts with knowing your daily target. Whether you're building muscle, losing fat, or maintaining your physique, getting enough protein is critical. This planner generates customized meal plans from a database of 80+ high-protein foods, automatically distributing protein across breakfast, lunch, dinner, and snacks to optimize muscle protein synthesis.</p>
            <p>Simply enter your daily protein goal, choose your number of meals, and select your dietary preference. The planner will generate a complete meal plan with specific foods and serving sizes, showing exactly how much protein each food contributes. You can swap individual foods to match your tastes while keeping your protein targets intact.</p>

            <h2>Protein Sources by Diet Type</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Omnivore:</strong> Chicken breast, lean beef, turkey, eggs, Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, fish, and whey protein provide the highest protein per serving with complete amino acid profiles.</li>
                <li><strong>Pescatarian:</strong> Salmon, tuna, shrimp, cod, eggs, Greek yogurt, and cottage cheese offer excellent protein alongside omega-3 fatty acids for heart and brain health.</li>
                <li><strong>Vegetarian:</strong> Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, eggs, whey protein, paneer, and cheese combined with lentils, chickpeas, and quinoa can easily reach high protein targets.</li>
                <li><strong>Vegan:</strong> Seitan, tempeh, tofu, edamame, lentils, chickpeas, pea protein, hemp seeds, and nutritional yeast provide substantial protein from plant sources.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Why Protein Timing Matters</h2>
            <p>Studies show that consuming 20&ndash;40g of protein per meal stimulates maximal muscle protein synthesis. Eating protein evenly throughout the day &mdash; rather than back-loading it at dinner &mdash; leads to greater overall muscle protein synthesis. This planner helps you achieve optimal distribution automatically, ensuring each meal hits the ideal protein range for your goals.</p>
        </div>
    </main>
</div>

<script is:inline>
var foodDatabase = {
